  "prompt": "What causes a tongue to turn black after vomiting?",
  "response": "A black tongue after vomiting is typically not a direct result of vomiting itself, but can be caused by several factors:\n\n1. Bismuth subsalicylate (Pepto-Bismol)\n- This medication can cause a temporary black discoloration of the tongue\n- Contains bismuth, which can react with sulfur in saliva to create a black coating\n\n2. Bacterial overgrowth\n- Vomiting can disrupt the normal balance of bacteria in the mouth\n- This can lead to an overgrowth of dark-colored bacteria\n- Condition known as \"black hairy tongue\"\n\n3. Dehydration\n- Vomiting can cause dehydration\n- Reduced saliva production can create an environment where bacteria grow\n- Can contribute to tongue discoloration\n\n4. Residual stomach contents\n- Dark-colored food or drink in stomach acid might temporarily stain the tongue\n- Bile or blood from forceful vomiting can also cause discoloration\n\n5. Potential medical conditions\n- In rare cases, could indicate an underlying health issue\n\nIf the black tongue persists or is accompanied by other symptoms, it's recommended to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.",
